Sure! To create a text shadow using CSS, you can use the text-shadow property. Here's an example:

```
p {
  text-shadow: 2px 2px 2px #000000;
}
```

In this example, the text-shadow property is applied to the <p> element. The first value (2px) specifies the horizontal offset, the second value (2px) specifies the vertical offset, and the third value (2px) specifies the blur radius. The fourth value (#000000) represents the color of the shadow.

You can adjust the values to achieve different shadow effects. For example, you can change the offset values to move the shadow in different directions or increase the blur radius to create a softer shadow.

Remember to include the text-shadow property in the CSS stylesheet and apply it to the appropriate elements.

You can use the text-shadow property to add a shadow to text. Here's an example:

```
p {
  text-shadow: 2px 2px 2px #000000;
}
```

This code will add a 2-pixel shadow to the text in the paragraph element. You can adjust the shadow size, color, and position by changing the values in the text-shadow property.
